                </div>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">48 Shades of Blue</h2>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Traditional Japanese color vocabulary names 48 distinct shades of indigo, from the palest "mizuiro" (water color) to the deepest "noukon" (dense navy). Each shade requires a different number of dips in the vat:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Kamenozoki</strong> (1-2 dips) — The lightest shade, "peeping into the vat"</li>
                    <li><strong>Asagi</strong> (5-7 dips) — A clear, light blue</li>
                    <li><strong>Hanada</strong> (10-12 dips) — Middle blue, popular for everyday fabrics</li>
                    <li><strong>Ai</strong> (15-18 dips) — Pure indigo blue</li>
                    <li><strong>Kachi-iro</strong> (20+ dips) — "Victory color," so dark it appears black</li>
                </ul>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">More Than Beauty</h2>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Indigo was valued not just for its color but for its practical properties. The dye is naturally antibacterial and insect-repellent, making it ideal for workwear, bedding, and baby clothes. Samurai wore indigo undergarments believing the dye would help heal wounds.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Today, research confirms many of these traditional beliefs. Indigo-dyed textiles show measurable antibacterial properties, and the color is gentle on sensitive skin.
                </p>

