                <div class="my-12 bg-gray-200 aspect-[4/3] flex items-center justify-center text-gray-500">
                    [Image: Indigo-dyed textiles drying - to be added]
                </div>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">What to Bring Home</h2>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Awa indigo products make exceptional souvenirs that combine beauty with practicality:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Tenugui</strong> (hand towels) — Versatile and packable, from ¥1,500</li>
                    <li><strong>Furoshiki</strong> (wrapping cloths) — Traditional gift-wrapping that becomes part of the gift</li>
                    <li><strong>Tote bags</strong> — Sturdy cotton canvas dyed deep indigo</li>
                    <li><strong>Scarves</strong> — Silk or cotton, light enough for any season</li>
                    <li><strong>Fabric by the meter</strong> — For those who sew their own treasures</li>
                </ul>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Identifying Authentic Awa Indigo</h2>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    With synthetic indigo widely available, knowing how to identify traditional dyeing is valuable:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li>The reverse side shows color bleeding through (synthetic sits on top)</li>
                    <li>Color deepens when rubbed, releasing surface indigo particles</li>
                    <li>Price reflects the labor—authentic pieces start around ¥3,000 for small items</li>
                    <li>Look for certification labels from Tokushima Prefecture</li>
                    <li>The color shifts slightly in different light (synthetic appears flat)</li>
                </ul>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif text-jp-black mt-12 mb-6">Caring for Indigo Textiles</h2>
                <p class="mb-6">
                    Natural indigo continues to develop with use and washing. To maintain its beauty:
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
                    <li>Wash separately in cold water with mild soap</li>
                    <li>Avoid direct sunlight when drying (shade dry)</li>
                    <li>Expect and appreciate gradual fading—it's part of the charm</li>
                    <li>Some color transfer is normal in the first few washes</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="mt-16 p-8 bg-white border-l-4 border-jp-indigo">
                    <h3 class="text-lg font-serif text-jp-black mb-4">Try It Yourself</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm">
                        Several workshops in Tokushima offer hands-on indigo dyeing experiences. The <strong>Ai no Yakata</strong> (Indigo Museum) provides excellent English-language tours and workshops ranging from simple tenugui dyeing (¥1,500, 30 minutes) to full-day intensive courses.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Author Section -->
            <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
                <p class="text-sm text-jp-gray">
                    Written by <strong>Smith Ikue</strong> — A Japanese local sharing authentic souvenirs and the stories behind them.
                </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Navigation -->
            <div class="mt-12 flex justify-between items-center">
                <a href="/category/kimono" class="text-sm tracking-widest hover:text-jp-indigo transition-colors">
                    &larr; Back to Kimono
                </a>
                <a href="/articles" class="text-sm tracking-widest hover:text-jp-indigo transition-colors">
                    All Articles &rarr;
                </a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>

    <Footer />
</Layout>
